<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-200-292  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 200 292.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 17 1989 v6 n15 p30(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CASE:W sought as NewWave standard development tool.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (licenses)Caseworks Inc. (licenses).andO;Ticker:    HWP.andO;Product:   CASE:W (Program development software) (licenses)NewWave (Graphical user interface) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     Computer-Aided Software EngineeringSoftware PackagesLicensingStandardization.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Hewlett-Packard Co. wants to make Caseworks Inc.'s CASE:W programming toolthe standard development environment for NewWave applications.andM;Hewlett-Packard officials are talking to Caseworks CEO Joseph Richburg aboutusing the CASE:W technology, but have not reached any kind of licensing ormarketing agreement, said David Pugmire, NewWave project manager in PaloAlto, Calif.andP;  Should the two firms reach an agreement, ''We intend to turnthis technology into a product that is available to NewWave applicationdevelopers,'' Pugmire said.andM;Hewlett-Packard, Microsoft Corp. and IBM officials all have acknowledged thatprogramming for sophisticated windowing environments is a particularlychallenging task for programmers.andP;  As a result, Hewlett-Packard wants to giveprogrammers access to development tools that help them build the interface,Pugmire said.andM;Understanding the ProcessandM;To work with NewWave, developers would use CASE:W as if they were building aMicrosoft Windows application, Pugmire explained.andP;  Hewlett-Packard wouldprovide a post-processor designed to modify the Windows source-code modulescreated under CASE:W and to add all the functions related to NewWave.andP;  CASE:Wincludes an expert-system knowledge base that contains all the rules andnaming conventions for building the Windows user interface.andP;  Thepost-processing system would substitute the Windows rules database for theNewWave rules.andM;Pugmire stressed that programmers still will have to write all the functionsand algorithms that relate to their specific applications.andP;  He also said thata tool such as CASE:W would work only for software developers who arecreating new software expressly for NewWave, rather than trying to portexisting Windows applications to NewWave, because of differences in functionnames between the two environments.andM;CASE:W originally was created as a development environment for applicationsrunning Microsoft's Windows.andP;  Caseworks, of Atlanta, introduced CASE:PM, adevelopment tool for OS/2 Presentation Manager applications, last week atComdex/Spring.andP;  In March, Hewlett-Packard demonstrated how CASE:W could beused to develop NewWave applications at Esther Dyson's Personal ComputerForum in Palm Springs, Calif.andO;</TEXT></DOC>